Here is a possible C solution, but it's taking a leap of imagination...

Assuming your source file is effectively 'interpretted' source code 
there is something I've experimented with which may be of use.

take a structured language... you have a very small number of 
possible constructs you can do (typically, iteration, sequence and 
selection... as used by JSP). You can vastly improve running time 
by exploiting this!

Instead of 'compiling' your source and then running it (and thus the 
goto's I assume) you should keep the structure. Parse the file and 
produce a 'tree' of structures which represent the system described 
by the source. For example:

struct retval {
	int type;
	union{
		int i;
		float f;
		char c;
		char * bleh;
	} value;
};

struct operation {
	void (*call)(struct retval * val, void* data);
	void * data;
};

struct selection_data {
	struct operation * ontrue;
	struct operation * onfalse;
};

struct iteration_data {
	struct operation ** oplist;
	unsigned int num;
}

...

You then write code to handle each of these types.... and hen you 
build the tree of the code you simply create the correct operation 
structures, define their functions and link them all together. The 
first operation is usually an iteration to begin with, so just hang 
everything off that and have a single operation at the root. Some 
example processing code would be:

#define DO_OP(zzop, zzval) zzop(zzval,zzop->data);

void iteration(struct retval * val, void * data) {
	unsigned int i;

	for (i=0;i<((struct iteration_data *)data)->num;i++) {
		DO_OP((struct iteration_data *)data)->oplist[i],val);
	}
}

The advantage of this is that only that which needs doing is ever 
done at any point. The problem is that it uses the stack quite 
extensively and there's the need to pass data back and forth 
through the execution tree.... but it might be faster if your 'input file' 
can be represented in this way.

I know it looks quite nasty but it's not so bad once you've coded it 
yourself! The hardest part is the parsing from the file to build the 
tree structure!

