what i suggested is a fairly effecient (and simple) way of 
interpreting source code.. but it has to be structured source code 
(like C or pascal or algol or whatever).

>From the info of what your trying to interpret, this won't be of any 
use.

I've never really tried writing an emulator, but I can probably guess 
at most of the issues. Can you select what the opcode can be 
yourself? If so, you might be able to be very sneaky. I'm assuming 
that 'i' (in your main) is the position in the 'program' you are and the 
somefunc array holds the program?

In reallity... you're very very unlikely to get much faster than what 
you have!

If you can alter your 'machine code' for the opcodes as you wish 
you might be able to get back a little speed (possibly) by doing 
something odd. If you can parse your file into 'machine code' of a 
very clever form you may get some (smallish) speed increase. It all 
comes down to splitting the instruction word into fields, and then 
processing the fields one at a time. For instance (in a hypathetical 
machine word)

| type | reg 1 | reg 2 |
 0001  0000   0001		/* move R0, R1 */
 0010  0001   0010		/* add R0, R1 */

and so in... for simple arithmetic operations this can be interpreted 
like:

reg1=registers+((instruction & REG1MASK)>>REG1SHIFT);
reg2=registers[instruction & REG2MASK];
switch( instruction & TYPE_MASK) {
	case TYPE_ADD:	*reg1+=reg2;
	case TYPE_SUB:	*reg1-=reg2;

	...
}

This is about as fast as you're likely to get on simple instructions. 
Once you start adding different addressing schemes or have muti-
word instructions a little more time will be taken. The good thing is 
that adding such features isn't very hard to do and that the code for 
doing the interpretation is fairly tight.

If speed is a massive concern still... you might consider 
compilation! LOL. from here, that's about the only thing left!

Ian Woods




