SAS and vbcc can inline functions.

> inline is a C++ 'feature' and was (AFAIK) considered and left out of
> C99 (not ther actually are any C99 implementations yet).

The "inline"-keyword is included in C99, however with semantics which AFAIK 
differ from C++ and most existing compilers.

Usually, the inline-keyword is rather useless as different compilers have 
different restrictions on functions to be inlined (just as with the 
register-keyword, it does not guarantee actual inline-expansion but is just 
a hint to the compiler). Also, compilers which can perform inline-expansion 
of functions usually will do so anyway when they consider it worthwile (and 
the appropriate compiler-options are used).

> Hoever, taking a pointer to an inline function is probably either
> impossible, or simply refers to a non-inline version 9as in.. a
> normal function).

Yes. I've yet to see a compiler inlining a function called via a 
(non-trivial) pointer.

