Czesc Gunther!

Dnia 15-Sty-01, Gunther Nikl napisaî:

>> pre V39 solution: SetPointer() on 2 clear bytes in chip ram (not
>recomended).
>  Why not?  FYI, it works with P96 too.

- compiler will generate two additional sections: one in chip memory (which
must be accessed by absolute addressing mode of cpu; program won't be
automagically relocatable anymore), and second one which relocate above
absolute address (If you aren't using A4 global variable pointer your's
programs will have a lot of them). It's not neccessary when you use "new
style" pointer handling.

- chip memory should not be used by modern programs especially in sections
(Chip memory will get smaller and more splitted in any case, no matter what
program is doing).

- when new version of OS provides functions to do something you should use
them providing old ones only for compatibility. It'll make your's program more
stable and fast (old functions are usually emulated by new one; I've no idea
is it true for SetPointer() because I have not AmigaOS source ;).

Regards!

