What you have to remember about C is that there is no concept of a 
string.
Instead C deals with strings as arrays of chars.

I assume Java dynamically allocates more memory to string sizes when
needed?  In C strings sizes are fixed unless you manually increase the
size!  (with malloc(), realloc(), AllocMem() etc.)

> Java makes it easy for me, I just have to add them together to
> concatenate a character on the end of a string. This is the current
> situation in which I am having this problem. msg->Code is my 
character.
> I want to use this character in the string parameter
> of this function: Text(RastPort,char *,length), the only way i have
> managed to do it so far is like this:
> 
> char strChar[]={msg->Code,NULL};
> Text(rp,strChar,1);

You have to be carefull with this.  It would work but strChar would
only be initialised to the correct value when it is defined.  i.e. if
msg->Code changed then the contents of strChar wouldn't change.

Another way would be:

char bla;
...
bla = msg->Code;
Text(rp,&bla,1);

The Text() function expects a pointer to the start of some data.  It
doesn't have to be null terminated (because you pass in the length).

> ints to strings:
> 	I want to be able to output integers using the printf(char *)
> function. This is  just for debugging purposes. Is there a library
> function that will take an integer and return a char*, or will i have 
to
> write one myself?

Yes, sprintf().  This works just like printf but you provide an
additional parameter which is a pointer to an array of characters. e.g.


char mystring[50];
sprintf(mystring, "xyz is %d", xyz);

Note that you have to make some space for 'mystring' (you can't just
do 'char mystring[]' and expect it to grow & srink).

Functions in C don't usually return a char* because the memory needs
to be allocated (and deallocated) somewhere.

> Also i have never yet been able to get the cout thingy working.

