  No, not all compilers accept "const".

On Mon, Jan 22, 2001 at 09:04:40PM +1000, Colin Wenzel wrote:
> Would someone like to explain the difference between a 
> "STRPTR"  and a   "CONST STRPTR"
> 
> What exactly does the compiler do with the  "CONST"  declaration
> that is different?

  "const" is a hint for the compiler that an object won't change. This
  information can be used during optimization and/or to decide where to
  place the object. By using "const" the compiler might be able to catch
  wrong paramter usage.

