  can.

> STATIC BYTE  dataarea[256];
> BYTE *pointer;
> pointer = dataarea;
> 
> The contents of the "dataarea" may change, but the
> address is CONST.

  On pointers you can use it at *both* sides of the "*". The meaning is
  different: one is a constant pointer and the other is pointing to
  a constant object. Of course you can use it together: a constant pointer
  to a constant object ;)

> I have always used STATIC to define a storage class that 
> doesn't move,  is there a relationship ?

  STATIC means that the definition is _local_ to the current compilation
  unit. The object isn't visible outside if the unit. You can use STATIC
  and const together. Most of the time thats what you want any way.

  Gunther




