const int i=5;
i++;

should produce an error because, as const, i can't be
modified.

const char *x="truc";

x[3] = 'a';
Wrong because x is a pointer to a constant char.

x++;
Ok because x is a pointer to a const stuff but is not
constant itself.


More interesting :
int my_func() const;

This means my_func() always returns the same result.
It should be useful for optimisation purposes
(according to the C++ standard) but i don't see any
compiler using this feature.


In fact, const allow the compiler to store some datas
in ther TEXT hunk instead of the data one (so no copy
needed for pure executable). const is also a good
thing
for prototyping.

For exemple

strcmp(const char *a, const char *b)

protect from modifying strings a * b inside the body
of strcmp().

