@NODE "Mail_295" " const methods "
From: "James S. Adelman" <j.adelman@ukonline.co.uk>
Date: 01-23-01 21:05:06
Subject: @{b}const methods@{ub}


> More interesting :
> int my_func() const;

> This means my_func() always returns the same result.
> It should be useful for optimisation purposes
> (according to the C++ standard) but i don't see any
> compiler using this feature.

The 'const' here specifies that the member function C::my_func() of
some class C does not modify the object of type C upon which it operates.
Only member functions declared const thus can be called upon an object 
declared const, and only member functions which do not modify the object can
be declared this way.  The only exception is those data members declared 
mutable, which can be changed by const members; this allows, for example
the storage of useful intermediate results for re-use.  
This type of constness is useful to protect const-typing, 
and presumably can be used in optimisation.

> Bye

> Laurent

James S. Adelman




