Hi Stephen,

On 26-Jan-01, you wrote:

> 
> I need to be able to compile MUI programs with GCC. I have a fully working
> GCC install and have generated the necessary MUI include files with
> fd2pragma.
> 
> However, the macro thing that is usually used (you know what I mean eg.)
> 
> VGroup,
>   Child, HGroup,
>      Child, FileListview(),
>      Child, DeviceListview(),
>      End,
>   Child, PathGadget(),
>   Child, FileGadget(),
>   Child, HGroup,
>      Child, OkayButton(),
>      Child, CancelButton(),
>      End,
>   End;
> 
> causes GCC to vomit "unterminated macro call" error messages. Is this just
> me or is there a known problem?

No, it's a problem with unterminated macros :) And that's caused by
following the (apparent) indentation rules in the MUI development docs,
which liquify your noodle if you're not careful! :)

What you should be doing is putting an End for every call that makes an
object, and it has nothing at all to do with the Child or WindowContents
macros. So, things like HGroup, VGroup, WindowObject, RectangleObject etc.
are all terminated with an End. Putting the Child or WindowContents macros
/in front of/ an object creation macro on the same line seems to be quite a
common style, and it looks good, but it's confusing because you are lead to
believe (from the indentation used) that the End's match with the Child's,
when in fact the End's are matching with the <whatever>Object's just to the
right of the Child's.

Erm, I hope I explained that clearly because it's kind of late here! ;)

Anyway, here's an example that I hope will help. Even if you can't
compile it (it needs stuff from Toolbar.mcc) I hope it demonstrates
reasonably well what I've just been ranting on about. To drive the point
home about the End's and the VGroup's, look at the very first VGroup that
gets used in the window definition. Notice that (by the indentation) the
matching End is directly under the VGroup macro, and /not/ under the
WindowContents macro, as you might expect if the it had been written

WindowContents, VGroup,

End,

Which demonstrates that it is the VGroup which we pair the End with, and not
the WindowContents. 

Hope this helps,

Giles Burdett



